    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:9a7e89ce-eeab-4805-99db-b5d8eeeebd83",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a lively and curious 9-year-old girl who attends third grade at a local elementary school. She has bright eyes and curly brown hair, though today she appears noticeably pale and fatigued, with dry lips and sunken eyes — classic signs of mild-to-moderate dehydration. She is lying on the examination table clutching her abdomen, grimacing periodically with cramping pain. Her mother reports that {patientName} has been vomiting since yesterday evening and has had multiple episodes of watery diarrhea — approximately 6–8 times in the past 24 hours. The most recent two episodes have contained visible blood, prompting her mother to seek medical attention urgently.\n\n{patientName} lives with her parents and a younger brother in a suburban household. She is generally an active child who loves gymnastics, painting, and playing with her pet hamster. She regularly attends after-school care, where group snack-sharing and close contact with peers are routine. She also participates in a weekly nature club at school, during which children frequently handle soil, plants, and occasionally visit outdoor farms or petting zoos — a lifestyle pattern that repeatedly exposes her to potential zoonotic and environmental pathogens. Most recently, she went on a school field trip to a local farm about 3 days ago, where the children handled animals and ate a packed lunch outdoors. Her mother suspects the illness may be related to the trip, as two of her classmates have also reportedly fallen ill.\n\nHer appetite is completely absent, and she has been unable to keep any fluids down for several hours. She complained of a low-grade fever since this morning and has had moderate stomach cramps that come in waves. The bloody stools have alarmed her mother significantly. She has no rash or joint pain. Her mother is worried and brought her in promptly after noticing her becoming increasingly lethargic and tearful throughout the afternoon.\n\n{patientName} is generally a healthy and happy child who enjoys attending birthday parties, swimming in the summer, and helping her mother bake on weekends. She is up to date on her vaccinations and has a known mild allergy to amoxicillin (urticaria) and a food intolerance to strawberries. She takes cetirizine daily for her allergic rhinitis and vitamin D3 supplementation. Her school has a good nutrition program, and she normally eats a balanced diet with regular fruits and vegetables. Her pet hamster at home is a potential reservoir for certain enteric organisms, and {patientName} frequently handles the animal without always washing her hands thoroughly afterward — a habitual risk factor noted by her mother. Notably, {patientName} has been taking a course of an oral proton pump inhibitor (omeprazole) prescribed two weeks ago by her paediatrician for reflux-related symptoms; gastric acid suppression is a well-recognised pharmacological risk factor that reduces the acid barrier against ingested enteric pathogens, potentially facilitating the establishment of bacterial infection such as Campylobacter or Salmonella following her farm exposure."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
